Building on the wormhole mechanism from EIP-7503, we formalize a zero-knowledge wormhole proof system where funds are committed to addresses derived from secret preimages and later claimed by proving knowledge of the preimage. We construct a two-layer recursive proof architecture using Plonky2 with FRI commitments. Client-side dummy padding and local shuffling at the first aggregation layer enlarge the effective anonymity set against balance-linking adversaries.

We give game-based security definitions and complete proofs for deposit binding, one-time withdrawal, spend-path exclusivity, value conservation, nullifier indistinguishability, and transaction unlinkability. We prove that computing the size of the anonymity set is #P-hard. Benchmarks show 20ms proving time per authorization and ~3.7ms constant-time verification for batches of 256, with a marginal on-chain cost of only 96 bytes per authorization, over 50x smaller than ML-DSA.
